Scenario:

In the telecommunications industry, customers can choose from multiple service providers and actively switch from one provider to another. Customer churn is defined as the percentage of customers who stopped using a providers product or service during a certain time frame. In this highly competitive market, some telecommunications industries can experience average annual churn rates as high as 25%. Given that it costs 10 times more to acquire a new customer than to retain an existing one, customer retention has now become even more important than customer acquisition.

For many providers, retaining highly profitable customers is the number one business goal. To reduce customer churn, telecommunications companies need to predict which customers are at high risk of churn.

As part of the churn project Teleco Executives would like to see and consider a time series analysis on revenue from the first two years of operation. Once they understand any patterns in the data, they feel confident in understanding the impact of churn currently.
The given time series data records the daily revenue, in million dollars, during the first two years of operation.

Data File being used: teleco_time_series.csv.
Data Dictionary: The data set: Consists of 731 rows (days) and two attributes. First row: 'Day': Day during first two years of operation Second row: 'Revenue': Revenue in million dollars.

Part I: Research Question¶
A.1. Research Question¶

Can information from the revenue time series dataset from the first 2 years of operations substantiate and predict organizational revenue growth, with some measure of confidence?

A.2. Objective¶

The objective for this analysis is to provide company executives with a time series analysis of revenue from the first two years of operations. To provide a deeper and more meaningful understanding of any patterns and trends. This report will support the executives with business intelligence they seek to enhance confident decisions-making.

Part II: Method Justification¶
Section B. Synopsize of assumptions for a time series model including stationarity and autocorrelated data.
B.1. Assumptions of time series models¶

A primary assumption of time series modeling is 'Stationarity'.

In research from Mohr (2020), fundamentally stationarity explains that time series have a constant mean and a uniform variance over time. While not remarkably significant for the approximation of parameters of econometric models, these characteristics are necessary for the computation of trustworthy test statistics, therefore, stationarity could have a substantial effect on model selection.

A seconary but equaly important time series assumption is 'Autocorrelated data'.

The autocorrelated assumption according to research from Hamilton (1994), is the same as when one generates a linear regression model in that the errors are independent. Specifically, the dependency typically materializes due to a temporal component. Error terms correlated over time are autocorrelated, or serially correlated. If error terms are autocorrelated, issues may occur when using ordinary least squares. Problems may be that estimated regression coefficients are still unbiased, but no longer maintain the minimum variance property required for accuracy. Also, the MSE (mean squared error) may seriously undervalue the actual variance of the errors. And the standard error of the regression coefficients can negatively underestimate the true standard deviation of the estimated regression coefficients.

D.1.d. Perform spectral density function¶

In research from Wikipedia contributors (2021,) the power spectrum S(f) of a time series x(t) describes the distribution of power into frequency components composing that signal. According to Fourier analysis, any physical signal can be decomposed into a number of discrete frequencies, or a spectrum of frequencies over a continuous range. The statistical average of a certain signal or sort of signal (including noise) as analyzed in terms of its frequency content, is called its spectrum.

D.2. Identifying an ARIMA model offsetting the observed trend and seasonality¶

The data is not stationary as we can clearly observe from the evidence that the p-value is greater than 5 percent and the test statistic is greater than the critical value. In addition, the conclusions can be drawn from visual inspection, we clearly see an increasing trend. All of which indicates that the mean and variation are not 0. Therefore, we cannot reject the null hypothesis as this time series is non-stationary.

According to new research (Chedalavada, 2021), non-stationary data is unpredictable in nature, by definition, and cannot be predicted or modelled. If we employ this non-stationary time series, the results may be inauthentic, and may parody a relationship between variables that does not exist.

In research from Swanson (2016) there are four highly cited time series models used for forecasting that might provide a solution to our non-stationarity hindrance. They are.

ARIMA model Holt Winters Exponential Smoothing TBATS models SPLINE models

The ARIMA model produces the most consistent results across a range of applications. In conjunction with smaller prediction errors and a tighter prediction range, compared to the alternative models.

ARMA model According to new research from (Mohr, 2020), ARMA (Autoregressive Moving Average) model forecasts apply advanced econometric modeling techniques to forecast time-series data by first backfitting to historical data and then forecasting the future.

ARIMA model Auto-regressive-integrated-moving-average (ARIMA) models rank as the fundamental pillar for time-series modeling.

SARIMA model The SARIMA model, (Seasonal Autoregressive Integrated Moving Average), which is used for time series in conjunction with seasonal components and the model we will utilize for this project. This model is an extension of ARIMA that adds seasonal terms. The parameters of sets not only encompass the ARIMA p,d,q, but also P,D,Q for seasonal concerns.

D.2.a. Differencing out the trend¶

The above differencing has produced a p-value to 0 and an average mean of 0, consequently removing trend from our analysis.

The results have provided an acceptable p-value (0.0) that can fit the ARIMA model. The auto_arima model will be fitted to the data to produce the optimum ARIMA paradigm.

The findings of the auto-arima according to new research from (Prabhakaran, 2021), encouragement the assumption that the preeminent model is (p=3, d=0, q=2) and seasonality (P=2, D=1, Q=0) [12] Where: (p) being the order of the autoregressive (AR) term equals the number of lags to be used as predictors (d) being the integrated (I) term equals the minimum number of differencing used to make the data stationary (q) being the order of the moving average (MA) term equals the number of lagged pre-forecast errors to be used

The findings of the auto-arima encouragement the assumption that the preeminent model is (p=3, d=0, q=2) and for seasonality (P=2, D=1, Q=0) [12] (p) being the order of the autoregressive (AR) term equals the number of lags to be used as predictors (d) being the integrated (I) term equals the minimum number of differencing used to make the data stationary (q) being the order of the moving average (MA) term equals the number of lagged pre-forecast errors to be used

These mixed models are called SARIMA(p,d,q)x(P,D, Q)_S, the lower case letters denote the orders of the nonseasonal components and the capital letters refer to the seasonal components.

From here we will reiterate our modeling with the auto-arima provided p,d,q assumptions.

Part V Summation and Inferences¶
E.1.a. ARIMA model selection¶

The selection of the Autoregressive Integrated Moving Average (ARIMA) model was fitted using the Auto-Arima function producing the autoregressive (AR) number of optimal lags (3), the ideal integrated (I) to compensate for the differencing (0), and the most appropriate order of the moving average (MA)(2) terms to be used. In both the seasonal and non-seasonal components. Seasonal concsisted of (P=2, D=1, Q =0), with seasons of 12.

E.1.b. Prediction interval of the forecast¶

The four intervals of confidence levels were tested at 80, 90, 95, and 99% of accuracy. Using the 95% statistical benchmark of the risk that the daily revenue will not be within the range of 11.33 million and 13.38 million is less than 5% for not meeting this forecast.

80.0% Confidence Interval: 12.36 between 11.69 and 13.03 90.0% Confidence Interval: 12.36 between 11.50 and 13.22 95.0% Confidence Interval: 12.36 between 11.33 and 13.38 99.0% Confidence Interval: 12.36 between 11.01 and 13.70
E.1.c. Justification of the forecast length¶

Considering that the time series was a meager two-years in length (731 days), the logic was to try and utilize the majority of the data points for training, and a smaller set for testing accuracy. Consequently, the choice of 400 days for training and 330 days for testing was determined.

E.1.d. Model evaluation procedure and error metric¶

The SARIMAX model evaluation procedure utilizes the error metrics of mean-square-error and root-mean-square-error. The mean-square-error is 3.7405, and the root-mean-square-error is 1.934 and the root-mean-square-error 1.934. Both metrics asses the confidence level as very high on accuracy.

The Mean Square Error is the average of square of difference between the predicted values and true values. Sklearn provides it as a function. It has the same units as the true and predicted values squared and is always positive. The closer to 0 the more accurate.

Root Mean Square Error is the square root of the mean square error. It is also always positive and is in the range of the data. Also assessed as the nearer to 0 the more accurate.
